    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-11-16T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-11-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="644"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d644">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.6359 Wolfram Ore/27</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName type="from"
                            >Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 2381</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-11-16">November 16,
                            1933</date>.<lb/>[Received December 18.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to refer to the Legation’s
                    despatches, No. 2326, of October 9, 1933, and No. 2355 (confidential) of
                    November 1, 1933,<note n="16" xml:id="d644fn16">Neither printed.</note> on the
                    subject of the Chinese government wolfram (tungsten) ore monopoly, and to
                    enclose a copy in translation of a Note from the Ministry of Foreign Affairs,
                    dated November 8th,<note n="15" xml:id="d644fn15">Not printed.</note> which
                    quotes the Ministry of Industry as stating that the agreement for the
                    exportation <pb facs="0700" n="598" xml:id="pg_598"/> of tungsten ore concluded
                    between that Ministry and Messrs. Arnhold and Company has been cancelled.</p>
                <p>The Legation is informing the Consuls General at Canton, Hankow, Nanking and
                    Shanghai, of the Note from the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, and in view of the
                    report communicated in the Legation’s confidential despatch No. 2355, the
                    Consuls General are being requested to inform the Legation promptly of any
                    indication of a revival of the government tungsten monoply or of a monopoly
                    sales contract.</p>
                <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                <closer>For the Minister:<lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">C. E. Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                    <lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Counselor of Legation</hi>
                </closer>
            </div>
